text: I like Iron Man, lets face it, his tech stuff is really cool. But as a person.. Captain America is so much better. In the winter soldier Cap was not about to just be the governments lap dog, he has a moral compass and knows what is right and stands up for it, which makes him very admirable. "This isn't freedom, this is fear", "I thought the punishment came after the crime", etc..   Thus, If Cap has gone rogue, he has a good reason and is probably correct for it, even if it is against corrupt authority. I am totally on Caps side, but I have to say this trailer makes him look like the bad guy and iron man like the good guy.. 2vs1 beat down doesn't look good.  I hope they explain this more in another trailer soon, because we need to see more of why captain america is right and tony is just being a corporate douche bag.

text: Seriously. There's a lot of negative aggro about not following some civil war  plot. I'm all for following the originals (if they are good ). But c'mon give credit where credit is due. The trailer actually looks to be introducing some epic, tear jerking, action packed super hero fight. If it doesn't follow an original story line... then how hard is it to think of it as something else random, alternate, whatever you can live, it if it's that important to you!  Fact is i'm lucky enough to know all the characters and a little of the relationship they have with each other. Judge the film on the special effects, on the action, on what it reveals and is viewable. Don't JUDGE on some silly criteria like history and following some original story plot. That would be extremely nerdy and seriously childish!

text: Hokay... First of all, let me say, that was just a fantastic trailer, I can hardly wait, it really cant come out soon enuff! 8(   BUT I do have sum overall concerns...  As you may or may not have seen, the trailer reveals the basic(but not complete) character structures of the divided teams during the square off scenes. And while the Black Panther reveal wuz absolutely freakn killer, there wuz sadly absolutely zelch footage of  characters like The Vision, Spider-Man, or Ant Man. If you include The Scarlet Witch that's three very new characters(TV,SW,AM), two of those three (TV&SW)have had very little screen time. And on top of that you have the introduction of not one, but TWO of completely new and high profile Marvel characters which are The Black Panther and Spider-Man. Taking all that jazz into account and you end up compiling several more unknown dynamics into the structure of the overall storyline . So there's actually ALOT more actually going on than everyone going ballz crazy over the apprehension of The Winter Soldier because of his past actions who ironically and quite possibly could be taking up the Captain America mantle at the end if Steve Rodgers ends up biting the proverbial bullet, which is entirely possible given the original storyline. And I say ironically because while Bucky has been in two previous Marvel movies already, he has little actual screen time and even less dialogue time. Because of this I fear the strong brothers in arms bond that Steve & Bucky share which consequently is one of the main factors that kick starts this "Civil War" showdown(so very important lol), probably will not be as emotionally charged and consequently might not be conveyed to the audience as strongly as they had hoped for between the two. BUT I highly doubt it will be the same case concerning the similar yet different brothers in arms bond between Stark & Rodgers which of late seems strained with possible unresolved tensions and resentment. And because the audience is so much more familiar with the two being the current two largest marketed Marvel Studios  characters and all, making their square off felt and recieved on a much higher level. That scene towards the end where Rodgers and Stark confront each other and say (Cpt) "I'm srry but he's my friend", (Strk) "So wuz I" followed by Bucky & Cap teaming up to take down Iron Man wuz just down right chilling.(also wanted to note that it seemed Bucky handled Capt's shield with great precision and adpt skill, giving more credence to the theory that Bucky might be assuming the Capt. America mantle at sum point either at the end of Civil War or sometime in the near future...   SO! Basically, regarding the plot you have the Bucky being the primary catalyst for the for the Civil War, meanwhile you also have the introduction of Baron Zemos and he's up to to God knows what while all this sh*t is going down, but is probably the  deciding factor that inevitably ends up uniting the fractured Avengers under a common enemy or goal. That in itself is already a sh*t ton of different dynamics in the story, but compounding it even MORE so when you factor in some kind of decent or semi-reasonable/logical back story and motives for Spider-Man and especially The Black Panther, and the Wakandian(?) Kingdom. I mean that ALOT of story content. Which probably will lead to two things. 1) The run time of the move will most likely exceed 3 hours (which in my opinion isn't necessarily a bad thinglol). 2) Thats a Hell'va lodda characters and possible confrontations which means sum characters are most likely gettin killed off. It's theorized that just like in original Marvel Civil War comic story that Steve Rogers (Cpt America) will be killed. Also, in the trailer it certainly looks like Rhodey (War Machine) has either sustained critical and mortal damage during battle or has actually seemingly been killed from the way Tony is holding and mourning Rhodey. . Also, I really hope they finally kill off Hawkeye lol. Sorry, It's not that I dont particularly like his character, but unlike the comics its just that he's the least interesting hero character in the Marvel Cinema Universe. That funny yet annoying and devilishly witty charismatic bit that his character has always been known for in the Marvel Comic Universe. Which I always thought to be rather strange considering so far Marvel Studios has rather successfully been able to transfered or even amplify humor from the comic book pages to the big screen.

text: They shouldn't show Iron Man as a bad guy in this movie. It's probably not their intention, but it kinda feels like it. Originally, the Civil War plot would be more like an Spider Man story. Spider deciding on which side he would be. Making Cap the protagonist and even putting his name on the movie makes him more like the 'right' one. And yeah, he's probably the 'right' one, but it's not like Iron Man is the bad guy here. They have different points of views and for some reason, this movie shows Iron Man kinda like the villain that Cap would have to take down. Anyway, that's just my opinion, because I really prefer Iron Man over Captain America, so yeah.

text: Basically, Cap will stop at nothing to protect a wanted felon. Though Bucky may be a "friend," Cap is breaking his own code of justice by keeping Bucky from the authorities.  In doing so, Iron Man and Black Widow try to reason with him, but Cap refuses to let "justice" fall into the hands of people he can't trust. I don't get it. Why doesn't he trust them? Cap saved the world twice with Iron Man. Does he not see? Iron Man is not an enemy. He's a friend. You could see the heartbreak in Iron Man's eyes. For some reason this feels strangely like Anakin versus Obi-Wan...  I'm sorry, all Captain America fans, I stand with Iron Man in this.

text: Can I just take a moment to stop and reflect on Robert Downey Jr.'s portrayal of Tony? You can actually see the hurt in Tony's eyes when he tells Cap that he was his friend too. Anyone who watched Age of Ultron could tell that while Cap and Tony had their differences, they also had a great friendship. Now, they're fighting and Tony's hurt. He doesn't have a lot of people to lean on but the other Avengers are people that he can lean on and now he's fighting Steve Rogers, one of his friends, and he doesn't know how to handle this. I just wanted to say that. That's my opinion and I'm sorry if no one else feels that way.

text: For those who question whether this should be a Captain America movie or an Avengers movie: THIS SHOULD NOT BE AN AVENGERS MOVIE! We're seeing much of the Avengers because the new team that's in place is led by Captain America. Unlike in "Winter Soldier," Captain America isn't part of S.H.I.E.L.D. after the old Avengers went their separate ways in the first movie. So if we're going to continue following Captain America, we're going to end up seeing the new Avengers as well. As for Iron man, who was part of the old Avengers team, the comic book focuses on his rivalry with Captain America, so that's why we're getting more of him too. Thor and Hulk are no longer part of the team, either. The actual "Avengers 3 (Infinity War)" is much bigger than this. That installment includes the Guardians of the Galaxy and goes well beyond the Avengers, S.H.I.E.L.D., or any civil dispute. THIS SHOULD NOT BE AN AVENGERS MOVIE!

text: Here is my take on Bucky possibly yelling Steve's dead at 1:59.  If you look closely at that scene they're in the same covered area seen later in the trailer when both Steve and Bucky are double teaming Iron Man. When Bucky is moving his mouth, it looks like a one on one fight.  So maybe something happened to Steve mid-fight (dead or most likely seriously injured-Iron Man has a lot of fatal gadgets)?  Or is it before Steve shows up?  Maybe War Machine shows up to even the odds and him and Steve are fighting away from the camera?  It does look like Bucky has enough rage to pull out Tony's core, which would kill him.  That's some kind of symbolism for "look at what you did to my best friend, I'm going to do the same to you!"  But that could be just his mouth moving seeing how he's in the middle of a fight, punched Iron Man, and trying to pull out his core with all his strength.  The guy is probably breathing heavy.  For what it's worth, in the comics Bucky does take over for Steve as Captain America while Steve goes into a temporary retirement.  He eventually comes back and Bucky goes back to being Winter Soldier (good guy).  In Captain America: Winter Soldier there were a couple of foreshadowing moments of Bucky holding the shield up and facing the camera when fighting with Steve (they even took a moment to zoom in and show it clearly).  He also does use it like Captain America would (using it as a shield and throwing it).

text: HEY EVERYONE! Did you KNOW??? That this is not how the Marvel Civil War actually starts?  And it actually involves an explosion during a fight between superheroes and super-villains in Stamford, Connecticut, that results in the death of hundreds of civilians. (This preceded the Sandy Hook shooting).  Tony Stark pushes for super hero registration to ease the public pain over the tragedy (much like our Democratic party with firearms registration).  Captain America is against registration because it jeopardizes the safety, identities and families of superheroes. (Much like the Republican party and the NRA wishes to abide by the American constitutional right to defend ourselves with firearms).  AND THIS MOVIE COMPLETELY SHITS ALL OVER THAT CONCEPT??? AND IS AN OBVIOUS CASH GRAB IN REACTION TO DAWN OF JUSTICE? WHICH IS ALSO A SHITTY ALTERATION OF DARK KNIGHT RETURNS?  Thanks Marvel, for destroying a politically relevant story line.

text: This is a Movie Review so if you are scared of opinions then don't bother reading.  Also I am not the best typer.   The VIDEO REVIEW is on my channel so if you want to see it go check it out. :)   Civil War was a film that I've been looking forward to since the first Avengers came out in 2012. It has been a long wait and finally it has come. I thought the movie was above average but I also did notice a couple of issues with it. It has amazing action and spectacular characters. Iron Man and Cap both have great motivations to be fighting each other. The new characters such as Black Panther and Spider Man are some of the best characters in the movie but my personal favorite was Ant man. Paul Rudd shined in this movie as some of the best comic relief during some serious moments. My only problems were that the movie is too stuffed in the beginning but becomes more focused going to the second half. Also that the villian was pretty lame with just not really being intimidating nor important. Last but not least is that Marvel isn't really willing to take that many risks with their characters and I elaborate more on that in my video review if you want to see that. The video review does not have spoilers. 8/10 Great and above average but with some flaws.
